Now I have a complete picture. Here's how to get categories in `preferences.html`:

---

## Two sources of "categories" in this project

### 1. User's saved categories (from session) — via `EdSvcUserInfo`

`EdSvcUserInfo.java:272` already fetches `categories` from the auth API response and exposes `getCategories()`. Use it directly in HTL:

```html
<sly data-sly-use.edSvcUser="com.dell.core.use.EdSvcUserInfo" />

<div id="preferences-container" data-categories="${edSvcUser.categories}">
  ...
</div>
```

This gives you the **user's currently saved category preferences** as a string (e.g. `"Cloud,Security,Networking"`).

---

### 2. All available categories (from Thingworx) — needs a Sling Model

The `CategoryService.java`, `Category.java`, `CategoryList.java`, and `Question.java` beans exist but are not wired to any model or servlet yet. You'd need to create a Sling Model like this:

```java
@Model(adaptables = SlingHttpServletRequest.class,
       defaultInjectionStrategy = DefaultInjectionStrategy.OPTIONAL)
public class PreferencesModel {

    @OSGiService
    private EndPointsService endPointsService;

    @OSGiService
    private EduServiceApiClient apiClient;

    private List<Category> categories = new ArrayList<>();

    @PostConstruct
    protected void init() {
        // Call your Thingworx categories endpoint
        String url = endPointsService.getEduportalApiEndpoint() + "/your-categories-path";
        // parse response into categories list
    }

    public List<Category> getCategories() { return categories; }
}
```

Then in HTL:
```html
<sly data-sly-use.model="com.dell.core.models.PreferencesModel" />

<div data-sly-list="${model.categories}">
  <h3>${item.category}</h3>
  <div data-sly-list="${item.questions}">
    <!-- question fields -->
  </div>
</div>
```

---

**Which one you need depends on your goal:**
- To show the user's **already-selected** preferences → use `EdSvcUserInfo.getCategories()` (already implemented, zero new code)
- To render **all available** category options for the user to pick from → create a `PreferencesModel` that calls the categories API endpoint via `CategoryService`

