content.text:
Sure! Let me explain everything line by line.

---

## Line 1
```javascript
var $jq = jQuery.noConflict();
```
jQuery normally uses `$` as a shortcut. But AEM also uses `$` for other things, causing conflicts. `noConflict()` tells jQuery "stop using `$`" and instead we use `$jq` as our own safe shortcut throughout this file.

---

## Lines 3-10
```javascript
$jq(document).ready(function () {
    var $headerElement = $jq(".dt-emc-header");
    var $categoryWrapper = $jq("#preferences-container");

    if (!$categoryWrapper.length || !$headerElement.length) {
        return;
    }
```
- `document.ready` means **"wait until the full page HTML is loaded, then run this code"**
- `$headerElement` = the page header element (contains user info like email, location)
- `$categoryWrapper` = the `<div id="preferences-container">` where the category buttons live
- The `if` check says: **"if either of these elements doesn't exist on the page, stop here"** — safety check to avoid errors

---

## Lines 12-23
```javascript
const defaultCategories = [
    "Big Data", "Cloud", "Converged Infrastructure", ...
];
```
A hardcoded list of all available categories. These are what gets displayed as buttons on the page.

---

## Lines 25-27
```javascript
const email = $headerElement[0].dataset.eid || "";
const language = $headerElement[0].dataset.language || "English";
const country = $headerElement[0].dataset.location || "";
```
Reads hidden data stored on the header HTML element (set by the Java backend). The `|| ""` means **"use empty string if the value doesn't exist"**. These are sent to the API later.

---

## Lines 29-34
```javascript
const headerCategoriesRaw = $headerElement[0].dataset.category;

let headerCategories = [];
if (headerCategoriesRaw) {
    headerCategories = headerCategoriesRaw.split(",").map(c => c.trim());
}
```
- Reads the user's **saved categories from the server** (stored in the header as a data attribute)
- `.split(",")` converts `"Cloud,Security"` into `["Cloud", "Security"]`
- `.map(c => c.trim())` removes any extra spaces from each item

---

## Lines 36-46
```javascript
let selectedCategories = [];

if (headerCategories.length) {
    selectedCategories = headerCategories;
    localStorage.setItem("selectedCategories", JSON.stringify(selectedCategories));
} else {
    try {
        const stored = localStorage.getItem("selectedCategories");
        if (stored) selectedCategories = JSON.parse(stored);
    } catch (e) {}
}
```
This decides **which categories to show as selected** when the page loads:

- **If the server gave us categories** → use those, and also save them to `localStorage` (browser storage)
- **If the server gave us nothing** → fall back to whatever was saved in `localStorage` from last time
- `localStorage` is like a small memory in your browser that persists even after closing the tab
- `JSON.stringify` converts an array to a string for storage, `JSON.parse` converts it back

---

## Line 48
```javascript
renderCategories(defaultCategories, selectedCategories);
```
Calls the function below to **draw all the category buttons** on the page, marking the correct ones as selected.

---

## Lines 50-53
```javascript
$categoryWrapper.on("click", ".dds__tag", function () {
    handleCategorySelection($jq(this));
});
```
**Sets up a click listener.** This says: *"whenever someone clicks anything with class `.dds__tag` inside `#preferences-container`, call `handleCategorySelection` with that clicked element."*

`$jq(this)` = the specific button that was clicked.

---

## Lines 55-78 — renderCategories
```javascript
function renderCategories(categories, selected) {
    let html = "";

    categories.forEach(function (category) {
        const isSelected = selected.indexOf(category) > -1;

        html += `
            <div class="dds__tag dds__preftag ... ${isSelected ? "selected" : "unselected"}"
                 data-category="${category}">
                <button type="button" class="dds__preferencebtn">
                    ${category}
                </button>
            </div>
        `;
    });

    $categoryWrapper.html(html);

    $categoryWrapper.find(".dds__tag").each(function () {
        if (window.DDS && DDS.Tag) {
            DDS.Tag(this);
        }
    });
}
```
- Loops through every category name and builds an HTML button for each
- `selected.indexOf(category) > -1` means **"is this category in the selected list?"** — if yes, add class `selected`, if no, add class `unselected`
- `data-category="${category}"` stores the category name on the HTML element so we can read it later on click
- `$categoryWrapper.html(html)` injects all the buttons into the page
- `DDS.Tag(this)` applies Dell's design system styling to each button

---

## Lines 80-94 — handleCategorySelection
```javascript
function handleCategorySelection($tag) {
    $tag.toggleClass("selected unselected");

    selectedCategories = $categoryWrapper
        .find(".dds__preftag.selected")
        .map(function () { return $jq(this).data("category"); })
        .get();

    localStorage.setItem("selectedCategories", JSON.stringify(selectedCategories));

    callEducationPortalPreferences(selectedCategories);
}
```
Called when you click a category:

1. **`toggleClass("selected unselected")`** → swaps the CSS class, which changes the button color (blue ↔ grey)
2. **Collects all currently selected categories** by finding every button with class `selected` and getting their `data-category` value
3. **Saves to localStorage** so your selection is remembered in the browser
4. **Calls the API** to save your preferences to the backend

---

## Lines 96-112 — showLoader / hideLoader
```javascript
function showLoader() {
    pendingCalls++;
    $jq(".dds__srch-data-loading").removeClass("dds__d-none");
    $jq(".dds__srch-data-container").addClass("dds__d-none");
}

function hideLoader() {
    pendingCalls--;
    if (pendingCalls <= 0) {
        $jq(".dds__srch-data-loading").addClass("dds__d-none");
        $jq(".dds__srch-data-container").removeClass("dds__d-none");
    }
}
```
- `showLoader` shows a spinning loading indicator and hides the content
- `hideLoader` hides the spinner and shows the content back
- `pendingCalls` counts how many API calls are still running — only hides the loader when ALL calls are done

---

## Lines 114-141 — callEducationPortalPreferences
```javascript
function callEducationPortalPreferences(categories) {
    showLoader();

    const payload = {
        preferences: {
            modalities: [],
            categories: categories,
            email: email,
            location: { country: country },
            language: language
        }
    };

    $jq.ajax({
        url: "/CashMicroServices/eduPortal/EducationPortalPreferences",
        type: "POST",
        ...
        success: function () { callRedisUpdate(categories); },
        error: function () { location.reload(); },
        complete: function () { hideLoader(); }
    });
}
```
- Shows the loader
- Builds a **JSON payload** with your selected categories, email, country, language
- Sends a **POST request** to the backend API to save your preferences
- **If success** → calls `callRedisUpdate` to also update the cache
- **If error** → reloads the page immediately (this is what happens on local)
- **Always** → hides the loader when done

---

## Lines 143-176 — callRedisUpdate
```javascript
function callRedisUpdate(categories) {
    const userKey = getCookie("userKey");
    if (!userKey) {
        location.reload();
        return;
    }

    showLoader();

    $jq.ajax({
        url: "/eduservice/cash.json/redisCache/updateUserPref/" + userKey,
        type: "POST",
        ...
        complete: function () {
            hideLoader();
            location.reload();
        }
    });
}
```
- Gets the `userKey` cookie (your session ID)
- **If no userKey** → reload immediately (user might not be logged in properly)
- **If userKey exists** → sends another POST to update the **Redis cache** (fast server-side memory) with your new categories
- **Always after Redis update** → reloads the page so the new personalized content appears

---

## Lines 178-183 — getCookie
```javascript
function getCookie(name) {
    const match = document.cookie.match(
        new RegExp("(^| )" + name + "=([^;]+)")
    );
    return match ? match[2] : "";
}
```
A helper that reads a specific cookie by name from the browser. Returns the value if found, or empty string if not.

---

## Full flow summary

```
Page loads
    → Read user's saved categories from server (or localStorage)
    → Draw all category buttons (selected ones highlighted in blue)

User clicks a category
    → Toggle button color
    → Update localStorage
    → POST to EducationPortalPreferences API
         ↓ fails (local env)     ↓ succeeds (staging/prod)
      reload immediately       POST to Redis update
                                    ↓
                               reload page
                               (shows updated personalized content)
```
